  "text": "Femoral PSA secondary to arterial access can be treated with ultrasound-guided compression with 70-100% efficacy. [CITATION_1] There is a better outcome if the PSA is slow growing, less than 6 cm, located below the inguinal ligament and has a narrow neck. [CITATION_2] The thrombin injections guided by US have become the treatment of choice for iatrogenic femoral artery PSAs, with the success rates ranging from 93-100%. [CITATION_3] In our patient, we opted to use a covered stent to exclude the PSA in order to avoid early recanalisation of the large lesion. Unfortunately, local experience with and literature on thrombin injections for this particular type of lesion were lacking. Using coils to embolise the PSA was a possible alternative. However, the neck was wide and many coils would have been needed to occlude the PSA, which might have left ",
